{
  "answer": "**No such couplet appears in the English translation of Mirza Ghalib's *Diwan-E-Ghalib* in this corpus.**\n\nI searched extensively using distinctive phrases like \"asylum[-]keeper\", \"keeper\", \"warden\", \"mad[ness/house]\", \"insane\", \"asking after/inquire\", and combinations with \"Ghalib\" across the English bodies. Results yielded many references to madness (*junoon*, *deewangi*) as a metaphor for love or passion (e.g., in ghazals 9, 13, 16, 28, 67, 76, 96, 97, 102, 207), but none describe an asylum-keeper (or equivalent like madhouse warden/guard/superintendent) asking after the speaker.[^1][^2]\n\nThe corpus contains *Diwan-E-Ghalib* (239 ghazals/chapters), but this specific image—possibly from a variant edition, recollection, or different translation (e.g., \"daroga-e-bimaristan\" or \"diwane-ka-darwaza\")—does not match the available English text.\n\n[^1]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 76 (\"Hum par jafa se tark-e-wafa ka gumaan nahi\"), [full chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/76-hum-par-jafa-se-tark-e-wafa-ka-gumaan-nahi/translation/).\n\n[^2]: *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, ch. 28 (\"Deewangi se dosh pe zunnar bhi nahin\"), [full chapter](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/28-deewangi-se-dosh-pe-zunnar-bhi-nahin/translation/).",
